"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447284","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-02","<p>Northumbria Community Rehabilitation Company has put in place an action plan to remedy shortcomings identified. We monitor the performance of all Community Rehabilitation Companies closely, to make sure they fulfil their contractual commitments to maintain service delivery, reduce reoffending, protect the public and deliver value for money to the tax payer. Operational assurance audit results are commercially sensitive, so will not be published.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-02-02T12:29:10.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447284/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447284/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447284/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-01-25","Northumbria Community Rehabilitation Company","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 18 January 2016 to Question 21777, if he will publish or summarise the outcome of the operational assurance audit of Northumbria Community Rehabilitation Company completed in June 2015 and any remedial actions required as a result of that audit.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","23949"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447285","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-02","<p>We hold providers rigorously to account for their performance and take action wherever they are falling short.</p><p> </p><p>Following operational assurance audits by the MoJ, seven CRCs have developed action plans. We will continue to monitor CRC performance closely. No CRC has been put on a formal Remedial Plan.</p><p> </p><p>Our probation reforms are designed to make sure that almost all offenders receive support on release, including, for the first time, those sentenced to less than 12 months.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-02-02T12:10:07.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447285/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447285/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447285/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-01-25","Community Rehabilitation Companies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 18 January 2016 to Question 22251, which (a) community rehabilitation companies have been issued with informal remedial action plans and (b) companies contracted to run probation services have failed an audit in each year since 2010; and what remedial action was required in each such case.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","23948"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447286","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-02","<p>Since the passage of the Legal Aid, Sentencing and Punishment of Offenders Act (LASPO) 2012, it has always been the government’s stated intention that the exemption for insolvency cases would be temporary. Commencement of Part 2 of LASPO’s conditional fee (or ‘no win no fee’) arrangement reforms for insolvency, was announced in December and will apply from April this year. The aim of LASPO’s reforms was to control the cost of civil litigation.</p><p>Ministry of Justice Officials discussed Professor Walton’s report with him, but the Ministry of Justice did not agree with his conclusions. Officials have also met representatives of insolvency practitioners who use no win no fee arrangements to fund these cases, as well as those who fund them in other ways.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","23864 ; 23889 ; 23890","2016-02-02T15:51:41.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447286/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447286/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447286/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-01-25","Insolvency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether he had considered the interim findings of the report of Professor Walton on the insolvency litigation landscapes, published on 10 December 2015, before making the announcement on 17 December 2015 to end the insolvency exemption from the Legal Aid, Sentencing and Punishment of Offenders Act 2012.","false","Biography information for Christina Rees","Neath","Christina Rees","23888"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447287","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-01-28","<p>I have received a report from the Coroner following the recent inquest into the tragic death from natural causes of a prisoner at HMP Parc in 2014. I have noted the matters of concern set out in it, which include issues of policy across the prison estate, as well as local practice at HMP Parc. The National Offender Management Service is working with the Director of the prison, and the other organisations to which the report has been sent, to ensure that the concerns are examined and appropriately addressed, and that the Coroner receives a response to his report within the statutory deadline.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-01-28T16:51:18.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447287/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447287/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447287/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-01-25","Parc Prison","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what investigation his Department is making into the concerns recently  raised by assistant coroner Christopher Wooley with regards to failures at HM Prison Parc.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","24022"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447288","Leader of the House","false","2016-01-28","<p>Future business of the House will be announced in the usual way.</p>","Epsom and Ewell","Chris Grayling",,"2016-01-28T17:11:55.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447288/answer","Biography information for Chris Grayling","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447288/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447288/answer",,,,,"34","Leader of the House","Leader of the House","2016-01-25","Trident","1","House of Commons","To ask the Leader of the House, with reference to his oral contribution of 21 January 2016, Official Report, column 1556, whether he has since been advised of the date on which the House will hold its debate on the maingate for the successor to the Trident programme.","false","Biography information for Dr Julian Lewis","New Forest East","Dr Julian Lewis","23832"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447289","Prime Minister","false","2016-01-28","<p>Details of Ministerial overseas travel is published quarterly and is available on the gov.uk website.</p>","Witney","Mr David Cameron",,"2016-01-28T14:30:33.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447289/answer","Biography information for Mr David Cameron","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447289/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447289/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2016-01-25","Prime Minister: World Economic Forum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, whether he visited the World Economic Forum in Davos, Switzerland, in January 2016, in his official capacity.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","24020"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447290","Scotland Office","false","2016-02-02","<p>I was pleased to be in Aberdeen on 28 January to announce a £250 million City Deal for the city and region. We are currently considering the Inverness and Edinburgh proposals and hope to make an announcement on next steps shortly.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2016-02-02T11:36:12.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447290/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447290/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447290/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2016-01-25","Local Government: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what recent steps the Government has taken on approving the City Deal proposals for the (a) Inverness, (b) Aberdeen and (c) Edinburgh city regions; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","23816"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447291","Department for Transport","false","2016-01-29","<p>Whilst Southern and Thameslink are used as operating names by the franchisee, they are in fact part of the GTR franchise, which operates the Thameslink, Southern and Great Northern (TSGN) Franchise.</p><p>Schedule 10.2 of the TSGN Franchise Agreement (<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/488198/tsgn-franchise-agreement.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/488198/tsgn-franchise-agreement.pdf</a> p.506) specifies how this franchise can be terminated by the Department.</p><p><br></p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-01-29T12:46:00.22Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447291/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447291/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447291/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-01-25","Railways: Franchises","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, in what circumstances his Department can terminate the (a) Southern, (b) Thameslink and (c) GTR contracts early.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","23811"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447292","Department for Transport","false","2016-01-28","<p>Following a successful procurement competition using the new STAR (Specialist Technical Advice for Rail) Framework Agreement, the Department has appointed a partnership comprising Arup, SNC-Lavalin Transport Advisory (InterFleet), and EY to provide services to support the Secretary of State in connection with his duties under Section 30 of the Railways Act.</p><br /><p>The contract is for 2 years and commenced in November 2015. It has an optional extension of 12 months which is exercisable at the Department’s discretion. The fees payable to the partnership are capped at £616k (excluding VAT) for the two years of the contract. In addition to core contractual commitments, further fees are payable at agreed daily rates for other services which include, but are not limited to, the full mobilisation of a public sector train operator.</p><br /><p>Following the successful award of the East Coast franchise to Virgin East Coast last year, it was not a good use of taxpayers’ money to maintain DoR’s full corporate structure on a ‘just in case’ basis. We have scaled back Directly Operated Railways operations and brought it in-house with the Department for Transport.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-01-28T15:37:51.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447292/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447292/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447292/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-01-25","Railways: Franchises","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what annual fee his Department will pay to (a) Ernst and Young in the UK, (b) Arup and (c) Interfleet for their advice to him on fulfilling his duties under Section 30 of the Railways Act 1993; and for what period those companies are contracted to provide him such advice.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","23836"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447293","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-01","<p>The Government remains committed to its manifesto target to double the number of journeys made by bicycle. In order to achieve this, all potential cyclists’ needs must be considered, including women and older people.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Government recently reaffirmed its commitment to cycling and walking, with SR2015 announcing funding support of over £300m. In addition, Highways England has committed to provide a safer, integrated and more accessible strategic road network for cyclists and other vulnerable road users.</p><p>By improving existing cycle provision and ensuring that cyclists are considered when designing and building new infrastructure then our roads will be more appealing to cyclists of all ages and ability.</p><p> </p><p>The Cycling and Walking Investment Strategy, to be published in summer 2016, will fully explain the Government’s investment strategy for cycling and walking.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-02-01T14:18:34.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447293/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447293/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447293/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-01-25","Cycling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he is taking to increase cycling among (a) women and (b) older people.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","23853"
