"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447318","Leader of the House","false","2016-01-28","<p>By custom and convention, the Order of precedence for the induction of new members of the Privy Council is that those wishing to take an Oath are appointed first, followed by those wishing to make affirmation. Other than this distinction, the Order of induction is alphabetical. Privy Counsellor appointments are published after each Privy Council meeting and are available at http://privycouncil.independent.gov.uk/privy-council/privy-council-meetings/.</p>","Epsom and Ewell","Chris Grayling",,"2016-01-28T17:16:39.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447318/answer","Biography information for Chris Grayling","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447318/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447318/answer",,,,,"34","Leader of the House","Leader of the House","2016-01-25","Privy Council","1","House of Commons","To ask the Leader of the House, what the order of precedence is for induction to the Privy Council.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","24039"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447319","Cabinet Office","false","2016-01-28","<p>Data is not held centrally on the number of individuals who have been made redundant from the Civil Service and then rehired, and can only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p>Since 2010 we have introduced into the Civil Service Compensation arrangements new provisions to prevent windfall benefits to anyone made redundant and then hired back into the Civil Service. These did not previously exist.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-01-28T15:51:40.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447319/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447319/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447319/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-01-25","Civil Servants: Re-employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many civil servants made redundant have been hired back in each year from 2011.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","24009"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447320","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-28","<p>The Landfill Communities Fund (LCF) is a tax credit scheme into which landfill operators contribute voluntarily. Since its introduction in 1996, the LCF has contributed over £1.4bn to community projects in areas affected by a local landfill site. However, as the LCF is a tax credit scheme, it reduces the government’s tax revenues. We therefore have an ongoing responsibility to seek value for money for the taxpayer.</p><br /><p>Autumn Statement 2015 announced changes to the Landfill Communities Fund. These changes were set out following consultation by HMRC on reforms to the fund. A summary of consultation responses, including those raising concerns about the Contributory Third Party (CTP) payment, can be found here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/reform-of-the-landfill-communities-fund" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/reform-of-the-landfill-communities-fund</a></p><br /><p>The government has received representations on the LCF reforms. We are taking views into consideration and our priority is to ensure that the Fund operates effectively and encourages money to be spent in the communities that need it.</p><br /><p>Information on the number of landfill operators contributing to the LCF is not held in the form requested. However, ENTRUST, the fund regulator, has published data on contributions to environmental bodies. This is available at:</p><p><a href="http://www.entrust.org.uk/landfill-community-fund/statistics/" target="_blank">http://www.entrust.org.uk/landfill-community-fund/statistics/</a></p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","24004 ; 24025 ; 24046","2016-01-28T14:35:21.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447320/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447320/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447320/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-25","Landfill Communities Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many Landfill Operators contributed to the Landfill Communities Fund in financial year (a) 2014-15 and (b) 2015-16 to date.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","24005"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447321","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-28","<p><strong></strong></p><p><strong></strong></p><br /><p>To date over £1.1million has been lent through Start-Up Loans issued in Brighton and Hove. Of this, over £268,000 has been repaid.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-01-28T17:27:40.6Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447321/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447321/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447321/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-25","New Businesses: Brighton","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how much was awarded to businesses in Brighton and Hove under the Government Start-Up Loans scheme; and how much of that has been repaid to date.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","23921"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447322","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-28","<p>The FCA does not directly regulate the activities of Symphony Communication Services LLC or any other electronic messaging platform. However, firms that are authorised by the FCA who use messaging services such as Symphony are subject to a range of applicable requirements, including the recording and storage of such tapes and electronic communications. The FCA is monitoring developments in relation to the use of Symphony by FCA-regulated firms.</p><br /><p>The FCA is also in touch with regulated firms to monitor how they are using new technology in this area, and any risks that may exist.</p><br /><p>Treasury Ministers and officials meet regularly with the Financial Conduct Authority to discuss relevant regulatory issues.</p><br /><p>As was the case with previous Administrations, it is not the Treasury’s practice to provide details of all such discussions.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","23899","2016-01-28T15:23:10.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447322/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447322/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447322/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-25","Banks: Computer Software","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what representations his Department has made to the Financial Conduct Authority on Symphony interbank communications software.","false","Biography information for Wes Streeting","Ilford North","Wes Streeting","23923"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447323","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-28","<p>At Summer Budget 2015, the Chancellor announced that the dividend tax credit will be replaced by a new £5,000 tax-free dividend allowance from April 2016, and that dividend tax rates would be amended from the same date.</p><br /><p>A tax information and impact note setting out expected impacts was published on 9 December. This is available to view at the following address: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/income-tax-changes-to-dividend-taxation/income-tax-changes-to-dividend-taxation" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/income-tax-changes-to-dividend-taxation/income-tax-changes-to-dividend-taxation</a>.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","23941","2016-01-28T12:20:40.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447323/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447323/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447323/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-25","Investment Income: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the potential effect on micro-businesses of changes included in the Finance Bill in relation to dividend taxation.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","23938"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447324","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-28","<p>At Summer Budget 2015, the Chancellor announced that the dividend tax credit will be replaced by a new £5,000 tax-free dividend allowance from April 2016, and that dividend tax rates would be amended from the same date.</p><br /><p>A tax information and impact note setting out expected impacts was published on 9 December. This is available to view at the following address: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/income-tax-changes-to-dividend-taxation/income-tax-changes-to-dividend-taxation" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/income-tax-changes-to-dividend-taxation/income-tax-changes-to-dividend-taxation</a>.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","23938","2016-01-28T12:20:40.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447324/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447324/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447324/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-25","Investment Income: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will publish monitoring his Department undertook on the impact on micro-businesses of the changes to dividend taxation included in the Finance Bill.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","23941"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447325","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-28","<p>The Prudential Regulation Authority is a subsidiary of the Bank of England and operationally independent of Government.</p><br /><p>Treasury Ministers and officials meet regularly with the Prudential Regulation Authority to discuss relevant regulatory issues.</p><br /><p>As was the case with previous Administrations, it is not the Treasury’s practice to provide details of all such discussions.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-01-28T15:21:46.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447325/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447325/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447325/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-25","Banks: Regulation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether his Department has made representations to the Bank of England regarding the regulation of any specific bank since May 2015.","false","Biography information for Wes Streeting","Ilford North","Wes Streeting","23927"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447326","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-28","<p>The Government is committed to exploring whether some form of “breathing space” would be a useful and viable addition to the range of formal and informal debt solutions available to consumers and creditors. Officials in HM Treasury and the Insolvency Service have been asked to discuss this issue with stakeholders with a view to identifying possible options and have begun work on this review.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-01-28T16:28:23.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447326/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447326/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447326/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-25","Debt Collection","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, by when he expects to publish the outcome of HM Treasury's consultation on the recommendation made in the review by Christine Farnish of the Money Advice Service, published in March 2015, for a breathing space mechanism to protect vulnerable customers making debt repayments.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","24043"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447327","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-02","<p>The information is not held in the form requested.</p><p> </p><p>Information on the number of taxpayers liable at the higher and additional rates of tax is set out in HM Revenue and Customs’ National Statistics table 2.1. This is available at the following internet address:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/429111/Table_2.1.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/429111/Table_2.1.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>This data covers the number of taxpayers aged under 65 years old as well as those aged 65 and over.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-02-02T17:47:09.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447327/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447327/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447327/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-25","Income Tax: Tax Rates and Bands","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many and what proportion of people aged (a) 21 to 64 and (b) 65 and over who pay income tax pay tax at the higher rate.","false","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","Wealden","Nusrat Ghani","24056"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447328","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-28","<p>The Landfill Communities Fund (LCF) is a tax credit scheme into which landfill operators contribute voluntarily. Since its introduction in 1996, the LCF has contributed over £1.4bn to community projects in areas affected by a local landfill site. However, as the LCF is a tax credit scheme, it reduces the government’s tax revenues. We therefore have an ongoing responsibility to seek value for money for the taxpayer.</p><br /><p>Autumn Statement 2015 announced changes to the Landfill Communities Fund. These changes were set out following consultation by HMRC on reforms to the fund. A summary of consultation responses, including those raising concerns about the Contributory Third Party (CTP) payment, can be found here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/reform-of-the-landfill-communities-fund" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/reform-of-the-landfill-communities-fund</a></p><br /><p>The government has received representations on the LCF reforms. We are taking views into consideration and our priority is to ensure that the Fund operates effectively and encourages money to be spent in the communities that need it.</p><br /><p>Information on the number of landfill operators contributing to the LCF is not held in the form requested. However, ENTRUST, the fund regulator, has published data on contributions to environmental bodies. This is available at:</p><p><a href="http://www.entrust.org.uk/landfill-community-fund/statistics/" target="_blank">http://www.entrust.org.uk/landfill-community-fund/statistics/</a></p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","24004 ; 24005 ; 24025","2016-01-28T14:35:22.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447328/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447328/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447328/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-25","