"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446722","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-03","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>Further to the answer given on 28 December to question UIN <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2015-12-11/19725/" target="_blank">19725</a>, the Department, or any authority investigating, would take into account all the relevant circumstances and the applicability of relevant legislation, before deciding whether to pursue a case.</p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-02-03T17:37:51.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446722/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446722/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446722/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-21","Franchises","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of 28 December 2015 to Question 19725, if, when considering complaints on breaches of the Trading Schemes Act 1996, his Department will take into account the contents of franchisees' contracts on the terms of trade and the relationship between the franchisee, master franchisor in the UK and overseas franchisor in order to determine (a) the number of master franchisors in the UK of an overseas based franchisor and (b) if the trading scheme was subject to the Trading Schemes Regulations, whether its contracts complied with those regulations; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for James Heappey","Wells","James Heappey","23663"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446723","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-29","<p>The loan agreement is a private document between UK Coal Production Limited and other UK Coal companies and The Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills. It covers both UK Coal Thoresby Limited and also UK Coal Kellingley Limited, the latter of which is still trading.</p><br /><p>The loan document is classified as Confidential Information and permission is required from UK Coal to release the loan document to third parties. We have sought permission from UK Coal and after due consideration the UK Coal board of directors have declined consent to release the loan document.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-01-29T14:49:40.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446723/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446723/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446723/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-21","UK Coal: Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will place in the Library a copy of the loan agreement that was reached with UK Coal in relation to the closure of Thoresby Colliery.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","23698"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446724","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-26","<p><strong></strong></p><p>All export licence applications are carefully assessed on a case by case basis against the Consolidated EU and National Arms Export Licensing Criteria, taking into account all relevant factors at the time of application. We draw on all available information, including checks using both open and classified sources, reports from non-government organisations and our overseas network, involving Desk and Post in the Foreign Office, when considering licence applications.</p><p /> <p>Foreign Office posts and departments in London monitor conditions in the respective countries – including human rights, regional tensions and the risk of exports being diverted to unintended end use – and advise on developments that might affect licensing policy.</p><p /> <br />","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-01-26T16:38:19.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446724/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446724/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446724/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-21","Arms Trade: Monitoring","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how his Department monitors the use of UK-manufactured arms by those countries to which they are sold.","false","Biography information for Dr Tania Mathias","Twickenham","Dr Tania Mathias","23714"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446725","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-29","<p><strong></strong></p><p>Ensuring that the apprenticeships levy works for all employers is a key priority for BIS. As such, we are engaging with both public and private sector employers, representatives from Unionlearn, and wider Government Departments on how the levy will operate and how they will build apprenticeships into their workforce training plans. We will be continuing engagement over coming months.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-01-29T13:42:14.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446725/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446725/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446725/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-21","Apprentices: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what discussions he has had with (a) public sector employers, (b) private sector employers and (c) UnionLearn on the implications of the Apprenticeship Levy on staff training budgets.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","23684"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446726","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-08","<p>Apprenticeship funding is not devolved and we have no plans to do so.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-02-08T17:42:44.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446726/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446726/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446726/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-21","Apprentices: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what discussions he has had with the (a) Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government and (b) Chancellor of the Exchequer on how the Apprenticeship Levy will operate in combined authorities to whom powers over skills and training are devolved.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","23685"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446727","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-03","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>Employers with a pay bill of less than £3m will not have to pay the levy. This is more than 98% of all employers. Small employers will continue to have access to government funding to support apprenticeships. Until the levy comes in, the apprenticeships scheme will continue to operate as it does now.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-02-03T18:00:50.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446727/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446727/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446727/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-21","Apprentices: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the potential financial implications for small businesses with 100 employees or fewer of the  Apprenticeship Levy.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","23686"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446728","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-01","<p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Traineeships are a demand-led, high quality education and training programme, designed to support 16-24 year olds educated to below level 3 who have little work experience but are strongly motivated by work. Traineeships have been designed to support progress into both apprenticeships and wider employment opportunities.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-02-01T15:43:47.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446728/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446728/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446728/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-21","Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, with reference  to his Department's document, English Apprenticeships: Our 2020 Vision, published in December 2015, whether the progression from traineeships is intended primarily to be into apprenticeships or into employment.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","23687"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446729","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-09","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>UKCES’s main support for the Department in respect of English Apprenticeships in 2016 is its ongoing work to map the new apprenticeship standards against frameworks and Standard Occupational Classification codes to help identify the remaining gaps in standards coverage.</p><p> </p><p>As announced in the 2015 Spending Review, in order to prioritise funding to allow the core adult skills participation budgets to be protected in cash terms, Whitehall Departments will be withdrawing their funding for UKCES during 2016-17. The Department for Business, Innovation and Skills is working with UKCES and other stakeholders to manage the implications of this decision.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-02-09T17:26:17.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446729/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446729/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446729/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-21","UK Commission for Employment and Skills: Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what role the UK Commission for Employment and Skills will have in 2016 in monitoring or contributing to the programmes to increase the number of apprenticeships and traineeships set out in his Department's document, English Apprenticeships: Our 2020 Vision, published in December 2015.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","23688"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446731","Cabinet Office","false","2016-01-27","<p>The Commission on Dormant Assets will will provide advice on which dormant assets can be brought into an expanded dormant assets scheme. The Committee remit will also include a suggested mechanism through which dormant assets could be redirected by Government to good causes.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-01-27T13:30:33.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446731/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446731/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446731/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-01-21","Dormant Assets Commission: Grants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what criteria have been set to access Dormant Assets Commission funds.","false","Biography information for Oliver Colvile","Plymouth, Sutton and Devonport","Oliver Colvile","23702"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446732","Cabinet Office","false","2016-01-27","<p>Nick O’Donohoe, outgoing Chief Executive of Big Society Capital, was announced as Chair of the new Commission on Dormant Assets on December 19 2015. The Commission is still being set up and I expect the appointments of commissioners who will work with the Chair to be finalised shortly.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-01-27T13:30:07.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446732/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446732/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446732/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-01-21","Dormant Assets Commission: Membership","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, who is on the board of the Dormant Assets Commission, announced on 19 December 2015.","false","Biography information for Oliver Colvile","Plymouth, Sutton and Devonport","Oliver Colvile","23670"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446733","Cabinet Office","false","2016-01-26","<p>The National Risk Register of Civil Emergencies (NRR) is the public-facing version of the National Risk Assessment (NRA), a classified assessment of the civil emergency risks facing the UK over the next five years. The NRR is published by the Civil Contingencies Secretariat, Cabinet Office. Due to sensitivities, beyond the detail contained within the NRR (particularly Chapter 3 of the <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/national-risk-register-of-civil-emergencies" target="_blank">2015 iteration</a>) the NRA methodology is not for public disclosure. However, every risk in the NRR is owned and assessed by a lead government department. Antimicrobial resistance (AMR) is owned by the Department of Health, which is preparing a paper for submission to the Lancet that sets out the analytical methods used to underpin the National AMR Strategy.</p>","West Dorset","Mr Oliver Letwin",,"2016-01-26T13:24:27.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446733/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Letwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446733/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446733/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-01-21","Emergencies: Drug Resistance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how his Department calculated the risk of antimicrobial resistance for the National Risk Register of Civil Emergencies published in 2015.","false","Biography information for Jeremy Lefroy","Stafford","Jeremy Lefroy","23657"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446734","Cabinet Office","false","2016-01-28","<p>Cabinet Office publishes Consultation Principles, which it expects all government departments to follow. They were most recently updated on 14 January in response to feedback from the Secondary Legislation Scrutiny Committee.</p><p>Principle G includes the line:</p><p>‘When the consultation spans all or part of a holiday period, consider how this may affect consultation and take appropriate mitigating action, such as prior discussion with key interested parties or extension of the consultation deadline beyond the holiday period’.</p><p>The Principles also make clear that formal consultation should only form part of the engagement process and that departments should make use of new digital tools and consider whether an iterative approach is appropriate.</p><p>The Principles can be found online on gov.uk and a copy can be found in the House of Commons Library.</p>","West Dorset","Mr Oliver Letwin",,"2016-01-28T15:49:07.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446734/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Letwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446734/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446734/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-01-21","Government Departments: Public Consultation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what guidance his Department issues on conducting public consultations during the summer recess.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","23597"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446735","Cabinet Office","false","2016-01-28","<p>The Civil Service has successfully changed the way it operates and become more efficient - it is now delivering far more, for less, than it did before 2010. The Government has delivered a range of policy changes over the last five years to modernise the Civil Service and save taxpayers money. During this time employee engagement rates have actually increased.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-01-28T14:47:42.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446735/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446735/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446735/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-01-21","Civil Servants: Job Satisfaction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the public sector exit payments cap on morale in the Civil Service.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","23612"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446736","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-01-26","<p>We are committed to consulting fully on our proposals prior to the introduction of any legislation and will announce further details in due course.</p><br /><p>We will adhere to any guidance published by the Cabinet Office in respect of the pre-election periods. We have and will continue to seek to work with the devolved administrations to deliver a modernised and reformed human rights framework for all of the United Kingdom.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2016-01-26T17:58:31.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446736/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446736/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446736/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-01-21","Bill of Rights: Public Consultation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what discussions he has had with Cabinet colleagues on the (a) timing of the consultation on the proposed Bill of Rights and associated measures and (b) effect of the purdah of the Scottish Government and dissolution of the Scottish Parliament on that timing.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","23582"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446737","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-02-05","<p>The advertisement is for an appointment for a limited period within the Department of Energy and Climate Change. The appointee will be approved by and report to an official at Grade 6 level within the Office of Unconventional Gas and Oil and will provide support to the team in its communications activities, which will include the production of core engagement materials for use with a range of different audiences in order to explain complex information in an easily digestible format. Once a suitable candidate has been identified, final approval will be sought from DECC HR.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-02-05T10:56:16.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446737/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446737/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446737/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-01-21","Government Departments: Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, with reference to the current advertisement on the Morgan Hunt website for a post of stakeholder engagement consultant, in which department the successful  candidate will work; who that person will report to; and who will approve that appointment.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","23531"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446738","Cabinet Office","false","2016-01-28","<p>All deputy directors have a responsibility for transparency policies whichreflects the breadth and importance of the agenda. An organogram of the Cabinet Office is available here: <a href="https://data.gov.uk/organogram/cabinet-office" target="_blank">https://data.gov.uk/organogram/cabinet-office</a></p><br />","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-01-28T16:55:08.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446738/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446738/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446738/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-01-21","Cabinet Office: Directors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, who the Deputy Director for Transparency is in his Department.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","23532"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446739","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-01","<p>We are unable to specifically identify whether alleged offenders prosecuted for committing a crime relating to financial misconduct worked in the City of London or any other geographical area. There are many criminal offences that could be construed as ‘relating to financial misconduct’ which are prosecuted by a number of differing authorities and a detailed answer could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>Since 2009 the Financial Services Authority and the Financial Conduct Authority have prosecuted 59 individuals for offences including insider dealing, breaching the general prohibition and creating false or misleading impressions or statements, seven of whom were acquitted.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-02-01T15:32:52.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446739/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446739/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446739/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-21","Financial Services: Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many people who work in the City of London have been prosecuted for a crime relating to financial misconduct since 2008.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","23566"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446740","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-26","<p>The government is committed to supporting the beer industry. The tax on a typical pint of beer was cut by a penny at March Budget 2015, building on the duty cuts at Budget 2014 and Budget 2013.</p><br /><p>The government continues to keep all taxes under review and decisions on tax policy are made as part of the Budget process.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-01-26T16:59:10.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446740/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446740/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446740/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-21","Beer: Excise Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will make it his policy to reduce beer duty by one per cent.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","23625"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446741","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-28","<p>Each year HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) uses the information it holds on its customers to remove around 400,000 customers from the Self-Assessment (SA) process. Customers will receive a letter confirming they no longer need to complete an SA tax return.</p><br /><p>HMRC contacts all customers who need to complete an SA tax return and offers support and advice on how to do this successfully to avoid penalties. Where a customer wishes to check whether an SA tax return is due they can check using the tool provided at <a href="http://www.gov.uk/check-if-you-need-a-tax-return" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/check-if-you-need-a-tax-return</a>. Tax returns issued will subsequently be withdrawn if a customer contacts HMRC to advise that their circumstances have changed and that a SA tax return is no longer required.</p><br /><p>If an SA tax return has not been filed within 6 weeks of the filing and payment deadlines, customers will receive a reminder either through email or SMS.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-01-28T14:29:21.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446741/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446741/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446741/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-21","Taxation: Self-assessment","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps HM Revenue and Customs has taken to reduce the number of people receiving inaccurate correspondence on the status of their tax return.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","23703"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446742","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-28","<p>HM Revenue and Customs has deployed a Demand Management approach since 2010 to reduce unnecessary telephony demand. This approach includes reengineering business processes, improving forms and guidance to provide greater clarity for customers and introducing a “Once and Done” approach on calls, where possible.</p><p><br></p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-01-28T14:30:57.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446742/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446742/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446742/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-21","Revenue and Customs: Telephone Services","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) has taken to reduce the number of unnecessary customer calls to HMRC telephone lines.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","23704"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446743","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-26","<p>Video Games Tax Relief is forecast to cost the Exchequer £10m in 2014-15. The first Official Statistics on the number of claims and cost of Video Games Tax Relief will be published in Summer 2016, allowing sufficient time for claims to have been submitted for the 2014-15 tax year. No estimate of the benefit for the economy as a whole is available.</p><br /><p>The forecast has been certified by the independent Office for Budget Responsibility and is consistent with their latest forecast of Corporation Tax receipts.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-01-26T14:49:33.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446743/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446743/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446743/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-21","Video Games: Tax Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many businesses benefited from video games tax relief in 2014-15; what the cost of that relief was to his Department in that year; and what the return on investment was for the economy as a result of that relief.","false","Biography information for Chris White","Warwick and Leamington","Chris White","23679"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446744","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-26","<p>The information requested is not available as HM Revenue and Customs does not routinely produce in-year estimates of the cost of abolishing Class 1 employer National Insurance contributions (NICs) for employees under the age of 21.</p><br /><p>However a full year costing estimate of this policy is published in table 2.2 of Budget 2015 which is available from the following address:</p><br /><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/416330/47881_Budget_2015_Web_Accessible.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/416330/47881_Budget_2015_Web_Accessible.pdf</a></p><p><br></p><p>The estimates for each financial year from 2015 to 2020 are as follows:</p><br /><table><tbody><tr><td rowspan="3"><p><br> Employer NICs: abolish for under 21s basic rate earnings</p></td><td colspan="5"><p>£ million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>2016-17</p></td><td><p>2017-18</p></td><td><p>2018-19</p></td><td><p>2019-20</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>-450</p></td><td><p>-500</p></td><td><p>-535</p></td><td><p>-560</p></td><td><p>-585</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><br></p><p>These estimates are based on the Survey of Personal Incomes (SPI) outturn data up to 2012-13, and then projected to 2019-20 in line with the Office for Budget Responsibility's March 2015 economic and fiscal outlook.</p><br />","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-01-26T14:41:13.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446744/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446744/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446744/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-21","National Insurance Contributions","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the cost to the public purse has been of the extension of the Class 1 Secondary National Insurance Contributions exemption for employees aged under 21 to date.","false","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","Burton","Andrew Griffiths","23691"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446745","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-01-26","<p>Section 151 officers of local authorities with social care responsibilities will be required to confirm whether their authority is using the flexibility to increase their council tax, and that any amount raised will be spent on adult social care services. The Department will expect that the figures provided will be reflected in established data returns to this Department during 2016-17.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-01-26T14:48:00.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446745/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446745/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446745/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-01-21","Social Services: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what mechanisms his Department plans to put in place to ensure that all the revenue raised from the social care precept will be spent on social care.","false","Biography information for Ruth Cadbury","Brentford and Isleworth","Ruth Cadbury","23683"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446746","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-01-27","<p>People find themselves facing homelessness for many reasons - and it is more than just a housing issue. Relationship breakdown, health and employment can all play a part. What is more, the costs of homelessness are felt across Government, through the criminal justice system, healthcare and the welfare bill.</p><p>I have re-established the Ministerial Working Group on Homelessness, to ensure we have a joined up response and a shared sense of mission across Government.</p><p>Through this Group, my colleagues and I will ensure that we have a coordinated plan to tackle and prevent homelessness across departmental boundaries.</p><br />","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-01-27T17:18:50.77Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446746/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446746/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446746/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-01-21","Homelessness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will initiate a cross-government strategy to prevent homelessness.","false","Biography information for Derek Thomas","St Ives","Derek Thomas","23648"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446747","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-01-29","<p>The consultation on the provisional local government finance settlement for 2016-17 closed on 15 January. We are considering carefully all the responses and other representations made and will present final proposals soon to enable local authorities to set their budgets for 2016-17.</p><p>At the outset of the current system of business rates retention in 2013-14, we said there would be periodic reviews to take account of changes to needs and resources. As part of the move towards 100% business rates retention by the end of this Parliament, we will work with local government on the approach to implementing these reforms, including on the treatment of needs and resources, and will consult on proposed changes.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-01-29T14:18:46.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446747/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446747/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446747/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-01-21","Local Government Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether the local government finance settlement will be subject to a needs-led review.","false","Biography information for Mr David Burrowes","Enfield, Southgate","Mr David Burrowes","23633"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446748","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-01-26","<p>There were delays to the procurement of the review which affected the timetable for fieldwork, leading to a clash with the General Election Purdah restrictions. In addition, the emerging complexity in the design and delivery of the review required additional fieldwork. All of which has contributed to the timetable for the review being extended.</p><br />","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-01-26T14:47:01.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446748/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446748/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446748/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-01-21","Supported Housing: Housing Benefit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 14 January 2016 to Question 21572, on supported housing: housing benefit, for what reason the evidence review was not published in November 2015 as planned.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","23622"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446749","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-01-29","<p>As set out in the voluntary agreement with the National Housing Federation, tenants of housing associations will be eligible for the equivalent discounts that are available under the Right to Buy (up to £77,900 and £103,900 within London). The Government has been clear that the sale of high value vacant council housing will pay for the cost of compensating housing associations for the discount, so the Right to Buy will be cost neutral. Ahead of full implementation, we have launched the Right to Buy pilot with 5 housing associations.</p><p>Overall there will be an ongoing evaluation of the Right to Buy pilot with the pilot informing the design of the full scheme.</p><p>We are engaging with local authorities and are in the process of updating data that will be used to help inform the high value threshold. Every home sold under the voluntary Right to Buy will result in a new additional home being built nationally.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-01-29T14:02:40.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446749/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446749/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446749/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-01-21","Right to Buy Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will publish the findings of his Department's right to buy pilots; what recent estimate he has made of the total cost of providing discounts to tenants eligible for that scheme nationwide and the number of council homes which will need to be sold in the course of that scheme; and what recent assessment he has made of the ability of housing associations to provide a like-for-like replacement for homes sold in the area local to those homes.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","23630"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446750","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-01-26","<p>The most recent local authority data outturn held by the Department for Communities and Local Government show the position as at 31 March 2015; Kirklees Council reported unallocated reserves of £38.0 million (this excludes other reserve balances for schools, public health and other earmarked reserves).</p><p>The usual measure of reserves used is non-ringfenced revenue reserves, which comprises the sum of unallocated and other earmarked reserves: in Kirklees case £114.2 million.</p><p>Full details can be found on the Department’s webpage at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/local-authority-revenue-expenditure-and-financing-england-2014-to-2015-individual-local-authority-data-outturn" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/local-authority-revenue-expenditure-and-financing-england-2014-to-2015-individual-local-authority-data-outturn</a></p><p><br></p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-01-26T14:44:26.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446750/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446750/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446750/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-01-21","Local Government Finance: Kirklees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what the unallocated financial reserves level was of Kirklees Council in the most recent local authority data outtrun held by his Department.","false","Biography information for Paula Sherriff","Dewsbury","Paula Sherriff","23575"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446751","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-01-26","<p>To date, 35 local authorities have registered an intention to claim under the activated Bellwin scheme but no final claims have yet been received.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton","23546","2016-01-26T15:00:26.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446751/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446751/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446751/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-01-21","Bellwin Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, which local authorities have recovered their costs for (a) flood prevention measures and (b) sandbags under the Bellwin Scheme to date.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","23545"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446752","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-01-26","<p>To date, 35 local authorities have registered an intention to claim under the activated Bellwin scheme but no final claims have yet been received.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton","23545","2016-01-26T15:00:26.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446752/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446752/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446752/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-01-21","Bellwin Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether borough councils which provide sandbags to all residents to protect their properties during incidents of flooding are able to recover the costs of those sandbags under the Bellwin Scheme.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","23546"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446753","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-01-27","<p>The Housing and Planning Bill requires the Secretary of State to define 'high value' in regulations.</p><p>We are currently in the process of updating data that will be used to help inform the high value threshold. Further details will be available shortly.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-01-27T17:10:18.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446753/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446753/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446753/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-01-21","Council Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, when he plans to publish the thresholds for council homes to be taken into account when calculating the levy on councils contained in part 4 of the Housing and Planning Bill.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","23605"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446754","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-01-29","<p>As stated by my rt. hon. Friend, the Prime Minister in his speech of the 7 October, the voluntary agreement between the sector and Government will make Right to Buy equivalent discounts available to 1.3 million housing association tenants.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-01-29T13:59:45.823Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446754/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446754/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446754/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-01-21","Right to Buy Scheme: Housing Associations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what recent estimate he has made of the number of housing association tenants who will become eligible for the right to buy by January 2017.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","23606"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446755","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-01-29","<p>I refer the rt. hon. member to the Written Ministerial Statement of 19 January, HCWS476, which sets out the Department’s intention to fund administration costs.</p><p>The Statement can be viewed at:</p><p>http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-statement/Commons/2016-01-19/HCWS476/</p><br />","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-01-29T14:03:32.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446755/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446755/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446755/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-01-21","Right to Buy Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the cost to the Exchequer of his Department's right to buy pilots.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","23607"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446756","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-01-29","<p>My rt. hon. Friend, the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government (Greg Clark) set out his proposed Council Tax Referendum principles for 2016-17 alongside the provisional local government finance settlement on 17 December 2015 [<em>Official Report</em>, Column 1722]. The full proposals are available at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/council-tax-in-2016-to-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/council-tax-in-2016-to-2017</a>. Final referendum principles for 2016-17 will be laid before the House for approval in due course.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-01-29T13:58:46.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446756/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446756/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446756/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-01-21","Council Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether he plans to reduce the council tax referendum level from 2 per cent to take account of his policy on the social care precept; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Stephen McPartland","Stevenage","Stephen McPartland","23515"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446757","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-28","<p>The temporary absence rules allow Housing Benefit to continue where under the normal conditions of entitlement it would not do so. They are therefore extensions of entitlement rather than withdrawals of it.</p><br /><p>It is the intention from April 2016, that Housing Benefit claimants who leave Great Britain for longer than 4 weeks will no longer be able to get Housing Benefit while they are away. This aligns the Housing Benefit rules with other benefits including Universal Credit.</p><br /><p>We intend that the period of 4 weeks could be extended in exceptional circumstances (for example, if their reason for being abroad is due to the death of a family member).</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-01-28T13:31:27.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446757/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446757/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446757/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-21","Housing Benefit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will make it his policy to enable special circumstances to be taken into account when making the decision to withhold housing benefit from people who are away from their homes for a period of more than four weeks.","false","Biography information for Meg Hillier","Hackney South and Shoreditch","Meg Hillier","23519"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446758","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-01-26","<p>Improving mobile coverage remains a priority for the Government, and our landmark agreement in December 2014 with the four mobile network operators (MNOs) to provide voice and SMS text coverage to at least 90% of the UK landmass by 2017 will significantly improve coverage in the UK. It guarantees £5 billion of investment in mobile infrastructure, and as a result mobile services will come to some areas for the first time. It will halve partial not-spots (where the is coverage from at least one MNO, but not all four), and cut total not spots by two thirds by end 2017. Additionally, Telefonica has a licence obligation to deliver indoor 4G coverage to 98% of premises in the UK by 2017. Other MNOs have indicated that they will match this commitment.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-01-26T15:14:36.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446758/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446758/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446758/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-01-21","Mobile Phones: Rural Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps his Department is taking to ensure the continued delivery of essential mobile telephone infrastructure to rural areas after the completion of the Mobile Infrastructure Project on 31 March 2016.","false","Biography information for Kevin Hollinrake","Thirsk and Malton","Kevin Hollinrake","23643"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446759","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-01-29","<p>For Other Ranks, the Ministry of Defence uses a long-standing and rigorous process of Job Evaluation (JE) to determine the pay treatment of each trade. In the current binary pay model which consists of High and Low Pay Bands, JE evidence assigns the role of the RAF Weapon Technician to the High Pay Band. In the new pay system, with its four supplements and greater flexibility, the same JE evidence assigns the Weapon Technician to Supplement 2, while other trades in the RAF's Trade Group 1 (TG1) (Aircraft Engineering) are assigned to Supplement 3. This does not mean there has been a reduction in the Weapon Technician's technical status or intrinsic value. It reflects the fact that the other trades in TG1 continue to score higher in the JE process and therefore continue to be treated differently in pay terms.</p><p>No-one will take a pay cut on transition to the new model and Service personnel will continue to be eligible for any Government approved pay award. Incremental progressions will also continue to be a feature of the new pay model, though rationalised.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","23660","2016-01-29T14:01:21.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446759/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446759/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446759/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-01-21","Air Force: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, for what reasons the trade supplement for a RAF weapon technician is no longer grouped with aircraft engineering trades under Armed Forces Pay Reform.","false","Biography information for Jo Cox","Batley and Spen","Jo Cox","23659"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446760","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-01-29","<p>For Other Ranks, the Ministry of Defence uses a long-standing and rigorous process of Job Evaluation (JE) to determine the pay treatment of each trade. In the current binary pay model which consists of High and Low Pay Bands, JE evidence assigns the role of the RAF Weapon Technician to the High Pay Band. In the new pay system, with its four supplements and greater flexibility, the same JE evidence assigns the Weapon Technician to Supplement 2, while other trades in the RAF's Trade Group 1 (TG1) (Aircraft Engineering) are assigned to Supplement 3. This does not mean there has been a reduction in the Weapon Technician's technical status or intrinsic value. It reflects the fact that the other trades in TG1 continue to score higher in the JE process and therefore continue to be treated differently in pay terms.</p><p>No-one will take a pay cut on transition to the new model and Service personnel will continue to be eligible for any Government approved pay award. Incremental progressions will also continue to be a feature of the new pay model, though rationalised.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","23659","2016-01-29T14:01:21.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446760/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446760/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446760/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-01-21","Air Force: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, by what process the trade supplement for an RAF weapon technician was decided under Armed Forces Pay Reform.","false","Biography information for Jo Cox","Batley and Spen","Jo Cox","23660"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446761","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-01-26","<br /><p>Steel has been sourced by our contractors from a range of UK and international suppliers, reflecting the need to ensure a competitive price and delivery at the required time and quality, and UK suppliers have made a significant contribution to this.</p><p>Supply chains are complex and the Ministry of Defence (MOD) does not hold a complete, centralised record of steel procurement for projects and equipment, either in terms of quantity or country of origin, over the past six years. But for the largest defence procurement project during this period, construction of the two Queen Elizabeth Class Aircraft Carriers, some 77,000 tonnes out of a total of 82,000 tonnes of steel used was manufactured in the UK.</p><p>Our new Government guidelines, which have been implemented in the MOD, will help UK steel suppliers to compete effectively for future defence projects.</p><br />","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-01-26T16:21:15.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446761/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446761/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446761/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-01-21","Ministry of Defence: Iron and Steel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what proportion of steel used in projects and in equipment procured by his Department in each of the last six years was manufactured in the UK.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","23620"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446762","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-01-26","<br /><p>We have provided education and training courses to Saudi Arabian Military personnel under existing government-to-government arrangements including the Managing Defence in a Wider Security Context, the Strategic Leadership Programmes, and Initial Officer training courses. These courses expose Saudi Military personnel to UK policy, and promote concepts of accountability, compliance with International Humanitarian Law and transparency. They are important in building skills which enable Saudi Arabia to deal appropriately with their own security problems, thereby contributing to regional security</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-01-26T15:39:02.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446762/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446762/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446762/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-01-21","Saudi Arabia: Military Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the oral contribution of the Prime Minister of 20 January 2016, Official Report, column 1411, if he will set out the specific activities being undertaken by British military personnel in providing training, advice and help to the Saudi Arabian military.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","23632"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446763","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-01-27","<p>As we set out in the 2010 Strategic Defence and Security Review, we will reduce the overall stockpile of nuclear warheads to no more than 180 by the mid 2020s. The Government is investing in the Atomic Weapons Establishment, which is responsible for supporting the entire life-cycle of the UK's nuclear warheads, from design and manufacture, to maintenance and certification of the existing warhead stockpile, and, ultimately, to decommissioning and disposal. In addition, the UK is co-operating with international partners - particularly the US and Norway - on a verification regime for the dismantlement of a nuclear weapon that could support any potential future nuclear disarmament treaty.</p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2016-01-27T16:08:49.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446763/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446763/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446763/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-01-21","Nuclear Weapons: Decommissioning","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the Government's policy is on further developing the necessary facilities and skills for the UK to become a world centre of expertise in the dismantling of formerly-armed nuclear warheads.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","23640"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446764","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-01-29","<p>The Defence Nuclear Safety Regulator (DNSR) assessment concluded that Exercise Senator 2011 achieved its stated objectives.</p><p>The DNSR assessment report contains five findings, four of which have been formally closed out. Work is in hand to address the remaining finding.</p><p>I shall place copies of the DNSR assessment and All Agency report in the Library of the House.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-01-29T14:01:22.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446764/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446764/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446764/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-01-21","Nuclear Weapons: Transport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what lessons were learned for emergency planning in the event of an accident involving the road transport of nuclear warheads from the Operation Senator emergency planning exercise held at HMS Gannet, Prestwick Airport in September 2011.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","23641"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446765","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-01-26","<br /><p>The case that the hon. Member refers to is complicated and sensitive and is still being reviewed by officials. I will write to him as soon as this review concludes.</p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2016-01-26T15:44:07.823Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446765/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446765/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446765/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-01-21","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, when he expects to reply to the letters to him from the hon. Member for Tewkesbury dated 20 July 2015 and 21 October 2015 on the treatment of veterans and the terms of the Military Covenant.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","23520"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446766","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-01-29","<p>Since 2003, the UK has played an important role in delivering training to the Iraqi Army through a range of training, mentoring and advisory activities. Due to the varied nature of the training it is not possible to give an exact figure of the numbers trained, but we do have figures for some specific areas of training.</p><p>Between 2004 and 2009 - as part of Operation TELIC - British Service personnel in the south of Iraq trained over 20,000 Iraqi Army soldiers. During this period the UK also supported the NATO training mission in Iraq, with British Forces providing advice and training to the Iraqi Ministry of Defence. The UK was the lead for officer education and training, and British mentors provided training and advice to the Iraqi Security Forces.</p><p>Under Operation SHADER, during 2015 and 2016, the UK has trained approximately 5,000 members of the Iraqi Army. This training has mainly focused on the delivery of Counter-IED training to support the Iraqi Security Forces in defeating Daesh.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-01-29T13:55:49.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446766/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446766/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446766/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-01-21","Iraq: Military Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many members of the Iraqi army have been trained by British servicemen since 2003.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","23569"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446767","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-01-29","<p>Since Operation SHADER began in 2014, the UK - as part of the Coalition - has trained approximately 3,000 members of the Kurdish security forces. The majority of those trained have been Kurdish Peshmerga.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-01-29T13:54:55.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446767/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446767/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446767/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-01-21","Kurds: Military Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many members of the Kurdish Peshmerga have been trained by British servicemen since 2014.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","23570"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446768","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-01-29","<p>Since 2001, alongside NATO partners, the UK has played an important role in developing the 350,000 strong Afghan National Security Forces through a range of training, mentoring and advisory activities.</p><p>During Operation HERRICK (2002-2014) UK Armed Forces personnel mentored and advised 3rd Brigade, 215 Corps of the Afghan National Army in Helmand. During this time, UK forces partnered Afghan personnel on operations, allowing them to learn from experience and enabling them, over time, to take the lead for operations themselves. The UK also supported the development of Afghan military instructors.</p><p>Since the end of 2014, as part of Operation TORAL, the UK has mentored and advised the Afghan instructors at the Afghan National Army Officer Academy (ANAOA) in Kabul. Up to 1140 Afghan cadets can be enrolled at ANAOA each year.</p><p>At present as part of wider NATO activity, the UK also has a small team deployed to Helmand to further assist the development of 215 Corps.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-01-29T13:54:28.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446768/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446768/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446768/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-01-21","Afghanistan: Military Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many members of the Afghan army have been trained by British servicemen since 2001.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","23571"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/446769","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-01-29","<br /><p>There are 9,360 British Service personnel permanently based on British military bases abroad. This figure includes those based in Cyprus, Gibraltar, the South Atlantic Islands, Diego Garcia, Germany, Canada, Kenya, Brunei, Nepal and Belize. This figure represents the number of Service personnel who are stationed at that location. It may differ from the actual number of people working on the base at the time, for example due to deployments. The breakdown of these figures into country and service is shown below; where countries have five or less personnel, these are rounded to zero and the country does not appear in the table. The Ministry of Defence regularly publishes the location figures for both military and civilian personnel, which can be accessed on the GOV.UK website at:</p><p>https//www.gov.uk/government/statistics/location-of-uk-regular-service-and-civilian-personnel-quarterly-statistics-2015</p><br /><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>UK Base Country</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Navy</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Army</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>RAF</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>TOTAL</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Germany</p></td><td><p>20</p></td><td><p>5,900</p></td><td><p>130</p></td><td><p><strong>6,050</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Canada</p></td><td><p>10</p></td><td><p>360</p></td><td><p>20</p></td><td><p><strong>390</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Kenya</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>210</p></td><td><p>10</p></td><td><p><strong>220</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Brunei</p></td><td><p>10</p></td><td><p>130</p></td><td><p>10</p></td><td><p><strong>150</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Nepal</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>20</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p><strong>20</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Cyprus</p></td><td><p>20</p></td><td><p>1,480</p></td><td><p>730</p></td><td><p><strong>2,230</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Gibraltar</p>